Chris Downey wrote:
&gt; 
&gt; Hello,
&gt; 
&gt; I just finished writing a JUnit test.  The test contains 5 values that
&gt; are initialized in setup and used to configure the class being tested.
&gt; 
&gt; For example:
&gt; 
&gt;    protected void setUp() throws Exception
&gt;     {
&gt;       
&gt;         priFacCost = 20789.0D;
&gt;         supFacCost = 4536.0D;
&gt;         supAdmPcnt = 5.7D;
&gt;         contPcnt = 5.0D;
&gt;         bidCostPcnt = 0.0D;
&gt; 
&gt;         pCostCalc = new ProjectCostCalculator(
&gt;                 priFacCost,
&gt;                 supFacCost,
&gt;                 supAdmPcnt,
&gt;                 contPcnt,     
&gt;                 bidCostPcnt       
&gt;         );
&gt;     }
&gt; 
&gt; This was great... until I realized that I need at least 5-10
&gt; variations on the values in order to test what happens if a zero or a
&gt; null is included in the ProjectCostCalculator parms.  Any ideas on the
&gt; best way to approach test design when you need to run it multiple
&gt; times with different data configurations?
&gt; 
&gt; The more I thought about this, the more I&#39;m wondering if there is a
&gt; known collection of JUnit test patterns.  Any thoughts on this?

_JUnit Recipes_, recipe 4.8, provides a JUnit-based solution.

For heavily data-driven tests, I recommend using Fit or FitNesse, rather 
than JUnit. FitNesse makes it easy to run the same test logic against n 
rows of input and expected output.
